Architecture review completed successfully for `7e119610…12e2dea4`, covering 008D2, 008E2, 008F, and 008G. No production code, protected files, or `docs/source/` material changed.

Key findings:

- Material Stage-4 edits retain a stale maker identity, allowing the latest editor to act as checker through another role.
- Compliance can downgrade an active PoA to draft and erase verification state.
- Mutable application status alone can create a security package without canonical final-sanction evidence.
- Signatures consumed by a verified tri-party agreement can subsequently be rewritten.
- Security package and PoA policy live under `legal_documents`, contrary to the source-defined `security_instruments` boundary.
- Domain modules depend on HTTP serializers, while action/error contracts and PostgreSQL concurrency evidence remain incomplete.

The three highest-risk integrity failures were independently reproduced as intentional RED regressions. Full findings are in [REVIEW_FINDINGS.md](/Users/amitkallapa/LMS/.ralph/worktrees/2026-07-14_185927_architecture_review/docs/working/REVIEW_FINDINGS.md), with the regression output in [01-independent-regressions-red.txt](/Users/amitkallapa/LMS/.ralph/worktrees/2026-07-14_185927_architecture_review/.ralph/runs/2026-07-14_185927_architecture_review/evidence/terminal-logs/01-independent-regressions-red.txt).

Two dependency-ordered corrective slices were created:

1. [008G2 — Stage-4 Maker and Verification Contract Closure](/Users/amitkallapa/LMS/.ralph/worktrees/2026-07-14_185927_architecture_review/docs/slices/008G2-stage4-maker-and-verification-contract-closure.md)
2. [008F2 — Security-Instrument Boundary and PoA Lifecycle Closure](/Users/amitkallapa/LMS/.ralph/worktrees/2026-07-14_185927_architecture_review/docs/slices/008F2-security-instrument-boundary-and-poa-lifecycle-closure.md)

008H now depends on 008F2, and 008H/008I have concrete PostgreSQL race-acceptance requirements.

All configured gates passed:

- Frontend: build, typecheck, lint, 293/293 tests
